what_you_could_do: Group all 195,826 messages into conversations using session IDs. Track conversation length, topics, and patterns over time.
Reconstruct exact reply chains for 190,427 messages. Build thread views showing who answered whom, measure conversation depth, detect broken threads.
Use 755 different identifier types (session, message, request, tool use, etc.) to link related data, deduplicate, and run fine-grained analysis without guessing.
Analyze 31,955 thinking blocks (15.8% of messages) separately from visible answers. Study which conversations had more reasoning and correlate with quality/cost.
Measure 44,883 tool uses (22.1% of messages). See which tools are used most, where they fail, and optimize workflows. Tool use is often invisible in chat UIs.
Process different parts of messages differently—e.g. search only visible text, or analyze reasoning quality separately from what was shown.
Study how usage changes over time (2025-10-02 to 2026-01-25). Find peak hours, trends, or correlate with events.
Analyze behavior by project, folder, or git branch. Project context is in the data; we can slice by it to see patterns per project.
Use 6,852 file-history snapshots to see which files were open when, and how that relates to what was discussed. That context is usually lost in chat UIs.
things_you_might_not_know: Every row in your data is a 'message' or similar unit. Stage 0 counts them, lists what's in them, and finds IDs and structure. Later stages process only what Stage 0 found.
Session ID ties every message to one conversation. Without it, we'd have to guess which messages go together.
Parent UUID says 'this message is a direct reply to that one.' We can rebuild the exact thread and who answered whom.
Thinking blocks are the model's internal scratchpad before it replies. They're usually hidden in UIs but show how it arrived at an answer. You have them in the data.
Tool-use means the assistant ran something (e.g. read a file, run code). That usage is often invisible in chat UIs but is fully visible in your exports.
Files are grouped by folder. We know exactly how many files live where, so you can scope analysis by project or directory.
The discovery manifest lists every identifier, every primitive we can act on, and the full structure. Downstream stages use only that—no hidden assumptions.

recommendations: OK: Data appears well-formed and ready for processing.
